<HEADLINE>
<P>
REV. JACKSON BLASTS TV ON LACK OF DIVERSITY; MEDIA: BOYCOTT IS THREATENED IF 
MINORITIES' VISIBILITY IS NOT IMPROVED. NETWORKS SAY THEY WILL RESPOND TO 
CRITICISMS AT CONFERENCE TODAY. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG BRAXTON and NICHOLAS RICCARDI, TIMES STAFF WRITERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Rev. Jesse Jackson on Friday repeated his attack on the television 
industry's record of cultural diversity, threatening to punish the networks 
with viewer boycotts if they do not immediately launch plans to improve the 
visibility of minorities in front of and behind the camera. 
</P>
<P>
 Meanwhile, executives from ABC, CBS, NBC and Fox said they will respond to the 
concerns of Jackson and several media watchdog organizations at a conference 
today at the Los Angeles Convention Center titled, "What's Wrong With This 
Picture?: Organizing to Win Cultural Diversity in Television and Film." 
</P>
<P>
 At a news conference following a student rally at George Washington High 
School in South-Central Los Angeles on Friday, Jackson accused the 
entertainment industry of "institutional racism." 
</P>
<P>
 "If our military in Haiti is red, brown, black and white, and when we pay our 
taxes we're red, brown black and white, why can't the media, which has so much 
power in our culture" be similarly representative, Jackson asked. 
</P>
<P>
 The appearance served as a preview for the conference -- sponsored by the 
Rainbow Coalition's Commission on Fairness in the Media -- to detail what 
Jackson termed a lack of minorities in positive roles on television series and 
a significant absence of African Americans, Latinos, Asian Americans, Native 
Americans and women among network news anchors, on prime-time entertainment 
writing staffs and in key decision-making positions. 
</P>
<P>
 "Moral appeals haven't worked, government regulation hasn't worked," Jackson 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Although he had threatened last July that the conference would target 
offending networks for a viewer boycott, Jackson said in an interview that the 
gathering now is primarily intended to inform participants of the "definite 
patterns" of racial exclusion, to put the networks on notice, and to form a 
battle plan if conditions do not change. 
</P>
<P>
 "We intend to meet with each of the network executives," said Jackson. "If 
they have a plan to be open and free, we will work with them. If not, we intend 
to use our consumer and viewer strength to open up the airwaves to be free and 
fair." 
</P>
<P>
 Jackson said the boycotts of stations and advertisers would most likely take 
place during the November sweeps periods, when networks put on special 
programming. 
</P>
<P>
 Other highlights of the conference include an opening address by George 
Gerbner, dean emeritus of the University of Pennsylvania's Annenberg School of 
Communication, who will deliver his results of a 20-year monitoring survey of 
stereotypes in network television shows. 
</P>
<P>
 Also participating in the conference are leaders from several ethnic media 
watchdog groups, including the Media Action Network for Asian Americans, the 
National Hispanic Media Coalition, American Indians in Film and the Assn. of 
Asian Pacific Artists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
