<P>
WEST VALLEY FOCUS: NORTHRIDGE; CSUN RECEIVES GRANT FOR CANCER RESEARCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF SCHNAUFER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A Cal State Northridge program that researches the spread of cancer has been 
awarded a $30,000 research grant from a private foundation. 
</P>
<P>
 The latest grant, awarded earlier this month from the Joseph Drown Foundation, 
brings the total to $200,000 given by the organization to the university's 
Center for Cancer and Developmental Biology, program head Steven Oppenheimer 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Researchers will use the funding to examine how cell adhesion works in sea 
urchins. Scientists say cancer spreads in part because cells lose their ability 
to adhere to each other. JEFF SCHNAUFER 
