<HEADLINE>
<P>
CANOGA PARK MAN ARRESTED AFTER STANDOFF; CRIME: POLICE SAY THE GUNMAN HELD HIS 
GIRLFRIEND AND HER FOUR CHILDREN HOSTAGE FOR FIVE HOURS. NO INJURIES WERE 
REPORTED. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 An armed man held his live-in girlfriend and her four children hostage for 
several hours early Friday until police forced the gunman out of his home with 
tear gas, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
 There were no injuries during the five-hour standoff, which began about 3:30 
a.m., Los Angeles police said. 
</P>
<P>
 The alleged gunman, Ron Adams, 43, lived with the victims in a two-bedroom 
townhouse on the 21000 block of Gresham Street, Police Lt. Steve Zipperman 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Adams was booked on suspicion of assault with a deadly weapon, police said. 
</P>
<P>
 Several neighbors said Adams and his girlfriend, Paula Primo, 35, often 
argued, and that police had been at the couple's apartment twice in the past 
two months to intervene in domestic disputes. 
</P>
<P>
 The most recent incident began early Friday when Adams' girlfriend phoned 
police and said Adams was armed with a .38-caliber revolver, and "threatening 
to injure himself and others," Zipperman said. Police said Adams was apparently 
jealous. 
</P>
<P>
 When police arrived, they evacuated nearby apartments and called the SWAT team 
and a hostage negotiator, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
 During the standoff, Primo's 17-year-old son and his teen-age girlfriend 
escaped from the apartment's garage where they had been living, police said. It 
was unclear whether they had been directly threatened by Adams. 
</P>
<P>
 After talking to police, Adams released Primo's 15-year-old son and 
11-year-old daughter, and finally, Primo, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
 "He didn't have any demands, he just wanted someone to listen to him," 
Zipperman said. 
</P>
<P>
 But when Adams refused to surrender about 8:15 a.m., the SWAT team fired four 
tear gas canisters through his window, forcing him outside, police and 
neighbors said. 
</P>
<P>
 Neighbors later said they often heard the couple fighting. 
</P>
<P>
 "You can't sleep at night," said Michele Thomas, who lives in a townhouse unit 
behind the couple. "You hear him being loud, you hear her, and then a child 
starts crying." 
</P>
<P>
 "If there's seven days in a week, they argue five," she added. 
</P>
<P>
 The apartment's resident manager, Vickie Smith, said Adams recently lost his 
job, but Primo had recently gotten a job. 
</P>
<P>
 "In the seven-year history of this building we've never had a police incident 
like this," Smith said. "No theft problem, no break-ins. Domestic disputes, 
yes, but nothing like this." 
</P>
</TEXT>
